civil rights organization

00:03:10.210 --> 00:03:11.090
in San Francisco.

00:03:11.090 --> 00:03:14.450
We've been around since 1972.

00:03:14.450 --> 00:03:17.620
My work is largely
representing immigrants

00:03:17.620 --> 00:03:19.340
who are facing deportation.

00:03:19.340 --> 00:03:22.470
And my client base is largely
southeast Asian refugees--

00:03:22.470 --> 00:03:25.380
Vietnamese, Cambodian,
Hmong, [INAUDIBLE],,

00:03:25.380 --> 00:03:28.490
Mien refugees who came
here in the '70s and '80s

00:03:28.490 --> 00:03:30.800
and are now facing
deportation, largely

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:33.570
for criminal convictions.

00:03:33.570 --> 00:03:36.230
And the experience is
really common across a lot

00:03:36.230 --> 00:03:39.260
of these refugee communities
of resettlement in the US,

00:03:39.260 --> 00:03:41.541
where the resettlement
process was really flawed.

00:03:41.541 --> 00:03:43.040
They were resettled
in neighborhoods

00:03:43.040 --> 00:03:45.800
that had really high
rates of poverty,

00:03:45.800 --> 00:03:49.010
high rates of unemployment,
high rates of incarceration,

00:03:49.010 --> 00:03:50.810
at the height of
the war on drugs.

00:03:50.810 --> 00:03:53.970
And a lot of them were funneled
into the prison system,

00:03:53.970 --> 00:03:55.880
the criminal system,
when they were teenagers

00:03:55.880 --> 00:03:58.840
and now decades later
are facing deportation.

00:03:58.840 --> 00:04:01.220
And it's become a
particular issue and problem

00:04:01.220 --> 00:04:03.650
as the Trump administration
has cracked down,

00:04:03.650 --> 00:04:06.320
especially on Vietnamese
and Cambodian communities,

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:08.504
with deportation raids.

00:04:08.504 --> 00:04:09.920
And it's one of
those issues which

00:04:09.920 --> 00:04:12.320
gets overlooked a lot in
a lot of the narratives

00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:15.280
around Asian experience.

00:04:15.280 --> 00:04:16.456
DAWN LEE TU: Thank you.

00:04:16.456 --> 00:04:16.890
RUSSELL JEUNG: Hi, everybody.

00:04:16.890 --> 00:04:18.230
My name is Russell Jeung.

00:04:18.230 --> 00:04:21.690
I'm Chair of Asian-American
Studies at San Francisco State.

00:04:21.690 --> 00:04:24.750
We're celebrating our 50th
anniversary of the Third World

00:04:24.750 --> 00:04:28.810
Strike and the founding
of Asian-American Studies.

00:04:28.810 --> 00:04:30.930
I've been living for
the last three decades

00:04:30.930 --> 00:04:33.930
in a low-income Asian-American
community in Oakland.

00:04:33.930 --> 00:04:37.470
And there, I think I see
a lot of pressing issues

00:04:37.470 --> 00:04:40.530
facing low-income and
working-class Asian-Americans.

00:04:40.530 --> 00:04:43.360
And if you talk about--

00:04:43.360 --> 00:04:45.900
you're not supposed to talk
about an oppression Olympics,

00:04:45.900 --> 00:04:49.650
but I do think that people
living on the margin,

00:04:49.650 --> 00:04:52.080
living on the edge, do
face a lot more struggle

00:04:52.080 --> 00:04:52.810
and suffering.

00:04:52.810 --> 00:04:55.890
And so I have a lot
of unhoused neighbors

00:04:55.890 --> 00:04:57.090
who are Asian-American.

00:04:57.090 --> 00:04:59.400
I actually have students
at San Francisco State who

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:01.870
are in Asian-American cities,
majoring in Asian-American

00:05:01.870 --> 00:05:04.610
Cities, living in their cars.

00:05:04.610 --> 00:05:08.400
And so issues of class and
intersectionality with race

00:05:08.400 --> 00:05:11.250
and immigration
and gender I think

00:05:11.250 --> 00:05:12.690
are really pressing
for our time,

00:05:12.690 --> 00:05:15.270
that a lot of the Asian-American
community isn't aware of.

00:05:15.270 --> 00:05:18.219
Besides homelessness,
on a broader scale,

00:05:18.219 --> 00:05:20.760
we're having mass displacement
of Asian-American communities.

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:23.630
You can see Chinatowns
disappearing.

00:05:23.630 --> 00:05:26.130
You see a lot of gentrification
in low-income Asian-American

00:05:26.130 --> 00:05:26.720
communities.

00:05:26.720 --> 00:05:30.160
So I find that
really significant.

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:31.180
DAWN LEE TU: Thank you.

