00:06:34.894 --> 00:06:36.185
of which never get represented.

00:06:36.185 --> 00:06:40.300
And it's just beginning to have
a voice in mainstream media

00:06:40.300 --> 00:06:42.210
and what the
dynamics of that are.

00:06:42.210 --> 00:06:45.720
And now I'm working on writing
films and shows so that I

00:06:45.720 --> 00:06:49.950
can contribute and continue
to talk in spaces like this

00:06:49.950 --> 00:06:51.520
to help make those connections.

00:06:51.520 --> 00:06:54.480
So for me, it's understanding
working in Hollywood,

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:56.460
also connecting that
to other industries

00:06:56.460 --> 00:07:01.020
and other communities, because
this is much larger of an issue

00:07:01.020 --> 00:07:04.242
and a much larger
strategy is necessary.

00:07:04.242 --> 00:07:05.200
DAWN LEE TU: All right.

00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:08.310
So how does diversity, you
know, or if you want to use

00:07:08.310 --> 00:07:11.220
intersectionality, diaspora--
whatever your word is--

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:14.070
show up in your
everyday life, and how

00:07:14.070 --> 00:07:17.354
does this impact your work?

00:07:17.354 --> 00:07:19.020
RUSSELL JEUNG: Well,
I was going to say,

00:07:19.020 --> 00:07:20.728
I think every
Asian-American and actually

00:07:20.728 --> 00:07:22.490
every individual
here will experience

00:07:22.490 --> 00:07:24.320
diversity in their families.

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:28.350
So I'm actually fifth,
sixth generation American.

00:07:28.350 --> 00:07:33.340
And my family has gone through
exclusion, segregation,

00:07:33.340 --> 00:07:35.960
a lot of the racial barriers
that a lot of people of color

00:07:35.960 --> 00:07:37.010
face.

00:07:37.010 --> 00:07:39.440
But even within my own
immediate family, I'm married--

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:41.390
I'm Chinese married to a Korean.

00:07:41.390 --> 00:07:44.900
We have two foster daughters
who are refugees from Burma.

00:07:44.900 --> 00:07:48.770
And then my extended family
are pretty multiracial.

00:07:48.770 --> 00:07:52.070
And so I think everybody,
even if your family

00:07:52.070 --> 00:07:53.600
was of the same
ethnicity, you know

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:57.020
you have generational divides,
you have gender divides.

00:07:57.020 --> 00:07:58.930
And then when we go
out to eat, you're

00:07:58.930 --> 00:08:01.380
not always eating Chinese
food and rice every day.

00:08:01.380 --> 00:08:06.170
So I think we all experience
diversity in our relationships

00:08:06.170 --> 00:08:09.752
and in our histories and in
just our day-to-day interactions

00:08:09.752 --> 00:08:11.710
with people at our
workplace or at our schools.

00:08:11.710 --> 00:08:16.250
So diversity is totally relevant
in our circumstances in the US.

00:08:18.998 --> 00:08:20.970
DAWN LEE TU: Anybody
else want to jump in?

00:08:20.970 --> 00:08:22.420
CHRISTINE MINJI CHANG: Did you
